% --- Executive Summary ---
\section*{Executive Summary}
Canonical is a rare asset in the current market: a pre-IPO infrastructure software company generating \$292M in revenue with an 83\% gross margin and established profitability. This model projects three years forward using publicly available financial information from Canonical's FY2024 filings. 

The core finding is that operating margins can naturally expand from 5.4\% to 15.0\% by 2027 without heroic assumptions. This expansion is driven simply by holding revenue growth at 16\% against a tightly managed ~10\% cost growth, yielding a base-case IPO enterprise value of ~\$2.2B.

% --- Section 1: ARR Bridge ---
\section{ARR Bridge \& Revenue Trajectory}
The 2024 bridge moves an estimated \$197M beginning ARR through new bookings (+\$30M), expansion (+\$20M), and churn (-\$12M) to exit the year at \$235M. 

Looking forward, gross additions are divided 60/40 between new-logo acquisition and account expansion. Churn is modeled stably at 6\% of the opening ARR balance. The base case compounds ARR to \$280M in 2025 and \$333M in 2026 assuming a 19\% net growth rate. The swing factor in these projections is net expansion—each point of net retention adds or removes ~\$3M from the 2026 ARR target.

% --- Section 2: Operating Leverage ---
\section{Operating Leverage: Path to 15\% EBIT Margin}
Holding revenue growth at 16\% while capping OpEx growth at ~10\% results in clean, structural operating leverage. Gross margin improves on scale by 100bps per year. As revenue scales, functional expenses decrease as a percentage of revenue: R\&D shifts from 27\% to 26\%, Cost of Sales from 17\% to 14\%, S\&M from 20\% to 19\%, with G\&A absorbing the largest percentage reduction.

EBIT scales from \$15.8M to \$68.4M over the forecast period—a 4.3x nominal increase. The margin path of 5.4\% $\rightarrow$ 9.0\% $\rightarrow$ 12.5\% $\rightarrow$ 15.0\% lands exactly on the medium-term target in 2027.

