% --- Section 4: Unit Economics ---
\section{Unit Economics \& Go-to-Market Health}
Unit economics display robust health. S\&M allocated to new logo acquisition implies a CAC of ~\$200K (based on ~175 estimated new enterprise logos). Against an enterprise ACV of \$175K (at an 83\% margin and a 4.5-year contract life), the LTV sits at \$654K. 

This generates an LTV/CAC ratio of \textbf{3.26x}, sitting comfortably above the 3.0x standard SaaS health benchmark. The CAC payback period is 16.5 months, well within the target 18-month window, providing headroom for continued S\&M investment without margin risk.

% --- Section 5: Scenario Convergence ---
\section{Scenario Convergence (2026 Outlook)}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Bear (12\% Growth):} ARR reaches \$295M. Margins continue to widen to ~13\% on cost discipline. Valuation anchors near \$1.46B. Downside is contained, and the business remains sustainably profitable.
    \item \textbf{Base (19\% Growth):} ARR reaches \$333M, landing the 15\% EBIT margin target exactly on plan by 2027. Implied EV of \$2.19B reflects a scale-adjusted peer parity.
    \item \textbf{Bull (25\% Growth):} ARR accelerates to \$367M, led heavily by account expansion. Assuming peer-parity valuation at 10x, EV reaches \$2.92B, demonstrating the upside available if net retention outperforms.
\end{itemize}

% --- Section 6: Methodology & Assumptions ---
\section{Methodology \& Key Assumptions}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Growth:} Base revenue growth 16\% p.a.; Subscription growth 19\% p.a.
    \item \textbf{Margins \& OpEx:} Gross margin path 83\% $\rightarrow$ 86\%; OpEx growth capped at ~10\% p.a.
    \item \textbf{Customer Dynamics:} Gross churn modelled at 6\% of initial ARR; New logo vs. expansion split at 60/40; Average contract life of 4.5 years.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Methodology Note (UK GAAP vs. Functional P\&L):} 
Operating expenses are modelled functionally (R\&D 27\%, S\&M 20\%, G\&A ~31\%) to reflect actual departmental spending, reconciling to the reported \$15.5M operating profit. This bridges the structural classification differences between Canonical's UK FRS 102 statutory accounts and a standard US-GAAP functional P\&L—which is the format an FP\&A team actually uses to plan and operate against. All underlying figures tie back to the FY2024 Companies House filing.

